<HEADLINE>
<P>
DANCE REVIEWS; CHRISTENSEN TROUPE ENTERS 'MACHINE' AGE AT LATC 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JENNIFER FISHER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There was no music in four of the five short works called "Machine" by 
Christensen Dance Company on Thursday night at the Los Angeles Theatre Center. 
Replacing it was a steady sound scape of dancers' breathing -- panting, grunts 
of exhaustion and pronounced exhalations. 
</P>
<P>
 Fatigue-as-accompaniment made sense in Joel Christensen's earlier pieces on 
the program -- the task-oriented "Blocks," and his solos "Boing" or "Tired," in 
which he frolics among tires he constantly rearranges. But in two new 
low-impact pieces, the often evenly paced and light physical efforts of the 
dancers (Christensen, Caroline Aizawa, Maryann Thomson and William Schurmann) 
didn't seem to warrant that amount of audible exhaustion. 
</P>
<P>
 The mood of "Kinetics," for instance, was more that of a warm-up, with dancers 
in pale spandex unitards tracing their own phrases, swiveling arms and hips as 
if to limber up. Keeping a casual rhythmic connection to four or five 
metronomes around the stage, they fell into partial unison and stopped in erect 
poses with angled arms and tilted flat palms. 
</P>
<P>
 Poses recurred with more regularity in "100" when a similar kind of noodling 
was alternated with a series (or fragments) of 100 classroom-like poses, called 
out by each dancer as performed.  
</P>
<P>
 It was hard to decipher a mood in these two works, which are definitely not in 
the hyperdance realm. The loose, detached, almost mechanical style and evenly 
spaced groupings were reminiscent of Merce Cunningham, without his attention to 
formal detail or the technical precision of his dancers. Christensen's 
combinations of everyday movement and jazzy or balletic modern dance aligns him 
with any number of postmodern dance-makers,  
</P>
<P>
 Technical glitches and an under-rehearsed look to group pieces didn't help, 
but Christensen's larger assignment is to give his company something more to 
breathe hard about. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Machine," performed by the Christensen Dance Co., Lo Angeles Theatre 
Center, 514 S. Spring St., downtown, tonight, 8 p.m., $8. (213) 485-1631.  
</P>
<P>
 JENNIFER FISHER 
</P>
</TEXT>
