<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: CANOGA PARK; VIDEO 
DISTRIBUTOR ORDERED TO GIVE $10,000 TO SHELTER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A video distribution company was ordered Friday to contribute $10,000 to a 
shelter for runaways and former prostitutes and banned from disseminating 
obscene materials. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Municipal Court Commissioner Barry Kohn imposed the sentence on 
Fantastic Pictures Inc. after its attorneys entered a no-contest plea to a 
criminal charge growing out of the firm's direct-mail videocassette business. 
</P>
<P>
 Kohn also placed the company on two years summary probation and banned it from 
disseminating materials depicting a wide range of sex acts, including rape, 
bestiality, sex with minors, sexual torture and murder for sexual 
gratification. All are illegal under state obscenity laws. 
</P>
<P>
 The donation to Children of the Night, a San Fernando Valley-based nonprofit 
organization, is to be made in two $5,000 payments next year, according to 
Deputy City Atty. Deborah Sanchez. 
</P>
