<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: VAN NUYS; AGGRESSIVE BOBBY SHERMAN FAN FREED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NICHOLAS RICCARDI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 39-year-old woman was released from jail in Van Nuys on Friday afternoon 
after authorities warned her not to go near former teen idol Bobby Sherman. 
</P>
<P>
 Ethel Richards, 39, had called Sherman, his office and his mother.She was 
arrested outside his Encino home. 
</P>
<P>
 If Richards doesn't leave Sherman alone, LAPD Detective Jeff Dunn said, "we're 
going to re-evaluate our decision not to press charges." 
</P>
<P>
 "I certainly have no ill feelings towards her," said Sherman in an interview 
Friday. "I had no recourse, I really didn't. . . . I don't do that to fans. 
Most of my fans, if they find my address, they'll ask for an autograph." 
</P>
<P>
 Sherman said Richards had called every Sherman listed in the telephone book 
until she found his mother, and also called his offices and manager posing as a 
record-company executive.  
</P>
<P>
 Sherman said police had advised him to notify them if she showed up at his 
home. Police arrested Richards about 5:15 p.m. Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Dunn said the decision not to charge Richards was made in a conference Friday 
attended by Sherman, detectives and the city attorney. 
</P>
<P>
 Richards spent Wednesday and Thursday nights in the Van Nuys jail. Sherman 
said she had written him a number of letters last month stating that when she 
was a teen-age runaway. Sherman lent her money to call home. NICHOLAS RICCARDI 
</P>
</TEXT>
