<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; LOSING COUNCIL CANDIDATE FACES 
COMPLAINT PARTY WAS TOO LOUD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Planning Commissioner Susie Newman, a recent council candidate, has been 
slapped with a misdemeanor complaint that she violated conditions of a 
temporary entertainment permit to play live music at her downtown restaurant on 
election night. 
</P>
<P>
 Police charge that music played on the night of Nov. 8 was so loud that it 
could be heard outside Newman's restaurant. Police also charge that the 
establishment's owners allowed dancing inside the Italian restaurant, called 
Mazzotti's, at 412 Walnut Ave. 
</P>
<P>
 "The bottom line is she violated the temporary live entertainment permit," 
said Police Chief Ronald E. Lowenberg. 
</P>
<P>
 Lowenberg said one of the conditions of the permit is that noise would not 
disturb surrounding businesses and residents. 
</P>
<P>
 "We determined based on complaints that in fact you could hear the noise and 
that it was loud and audible beyond the property of Mazzotti's," Lowenberg 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police said the Orange County district attorney's office is handling the case 
because of Newman's role as a public official. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman, who held her election night party at her restaurant, said she received 
notice of the complaint -- a misdemeanor violation -- in her home mail on 
Friday. The complaint summons her to appear Jan. 4 in West Court in Westminster 
to enter a plea. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman, co-owner of the restaurant with Leonard Mazzotti, said that the 
charges are petty and that they also jeopardize the restaurant's license to 
sell liquor. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman, who came in fifth out of 22 candidates vying for four open seats on 
the council, said that the charge "no question is harassment." 
</P>
<P>
 Lowenberg said Newman's charge of harassment is "ludicrous." 
</P>
<P>
 "We have better things to do than harass," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Newman said police arrived at the restaurant Nov. 7 because of noise 
complaints, and as a result the band stopped playing about 10:30 p.m. The next 
night, she said, the music ended by 10:15 p.m. Of the dancing, Newman said her 
supporters were merely reacting to incoming election results on her status in 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
 "They're picking on me, and I just ran for public office. I have knowledge how 
the system works -- imagine how the other people who have less knowledge of the 
system feel about getting a fair shake."DEBRA CANO 
</P>
</TEXT>
