<HEADLINE>
<P>
SEX TAPE DISTRIBUTOR FINED $10,000 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LESLIE BERGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Canoga Park distributor of sex videotapes was ordered to donate $10,000 to 
Children of the Night, the nonprofit group that helps young runaways, after 
being convicted of a misdemeanor for selling obscene videos, the city 
attorney's office said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Fantastic Pictures Inc. was also placed on two years' probation and barred 
from disseminating any materials depicting rape, bestiality, sex with minors or 
other illegal acts. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Municipal Court Commissioner Barry Kohn imposed the sentence after 
company attorneys entered a no-contest plea to a charge of committing a public 
nuisance. 
</P>
<P>
 The case began in January, when undercover LAPD vice detectives attended a 
consumer electronics show in Las Vegas and spotted brochures for videos at a 
booth operated by Zane Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
 Detectives learned that Zane Entertainment and Fantastic Pictures were under 
common management from 21528 Osborne St., Canoga Park. They conducted 
surveillance, made two undercover buys of videotapes and conducted a search of 
the offices, finding the evidence for Friday's conviction. LESLIE BERGER 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
