<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN SECTION FOOTBALL PLAYOFFS NCAA VOLLEYBALL REGIONALS; DIVISION X; 
ORANGE LUTHERAN VS. VAN NUYS MONTCLAIR PREP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 RECORDS--Orange Lutheran (11-2), Montclair Prep (10-1). 
</P>
<P>
 SITE--Los Angeles Valley College, 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 TV--Orange County Newschannel, 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
 ORANGE LUTHERAN--Was picked to finish last in the Olympic League. It has 
exceeded those expectations. It was co-champion with Cerritos Valley Christian 
(the first league championship in school history), and has reached its first 
title game. For much of the year, the Lancers have relied on a multifaceted 
offensive scheme that swings from the shotgun to the option, and has allowed 
them to average 31 points per game. In the last two playoff contests against 
Phelan Serrano and San Pedro Mary Star of the Sea, the Lancers relied on 
defense. They got a fumble recovery against the Diamondbacks to win, 22-19, and 
stopped a two-point conversion attempt by the Stars in a 7-6 overtime victory 
in the semifinals. Orange Lutheran again looks to their big three--senior 
quarterback Joe Juliano (1,455 yards passing, 950 yards rushing), junior 
running back Che Holloway (1,139 yards rushing, 19 touchdowns) and sophomore 
receiver Michael Crawford (29 receptions, 502 yards, six touchdowns) to bring 
home the trophy. 
</P>
<P>
 MONTCLAIR PREP--Big. Fast. Talented. Here are six more applicable words: It 
doesn't belong in this division. But it is here nonetheless, with an excellent 
shot at winning its second Division X title in four years. The team name is 
Mounties but it should be Raiders, as this is a team Al Davis would love. 
Montclair Prep is plastered with an outlaw image--it does not have a league 
affiliation and plays to intimidate. What the Mounties do best on offense is 
run. Junior Akil Anderson has 1,432 yards and 14 touchdowns, but 871 yards and 
eight touchdowns have come in the past three playoff games. In the 50-8 rout of 
Big Bear two weeks ago, Anderson ran for 418 yards, tying the state single-game 
record set by Agoura's Darrin Rogers in 1985. He also scored four times. 
</P>
<P>
 KEY TO THE GAME--Defense. Orange Lutheran, whose unit has been dwarfed in 
nearly every game this season, cannot allow the Mounties to run. Montclair must 
control Juliano. 
</P>
<P>
 CONSENSUS--Orange Lutheran might be "The Little Engine That Could," but 
Montclair Prep is the big machine that can. Mounties, 28-14. THE LINEUPS 
</P>
